<p>
	The 
	<a class="external" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentine_economic_crisis_%281999-2002%29">devaluation of the peso</a>
 in 2002 was a disaster for Argentines, and a boon to foreign tourists. Suddenly, those of us earning wages in U.S. dollars could encounter luxury goods at what we consider bargain prices in the shopping districts of Buenos Aires. Soon many people traveling to Argentina were advised to shop aggressively and take advantage of the favorable exchange rate. 
</p>
<p>
	I'm not much of a shopper at home. I didn't expect to degenerate into a shopping fiend in Buenos Aires, and didn't. My customs form re-entering the U.S. required no supplement. 
</p>
<p>
	Nevertheless, it is alluring to see the low prices on the tags. 
</p>
<p>
	"I feel like a Japanese tourist in the 1980's," my husband Michael said. We were probably staring at a display of fur coats or designer jeans: things I would never wear, and would question just why I bought them the instant I unpacked my suitcase at home. One thing that kept me abstemious in the boutiques is that the clothing styles tended to the same regrettable 1970's retro fashion that afflicts the U.S. at present. I don't care how cheap they are in dollars; hip-huggers are ugly at any price. 
</p>
<p>
	So my South American spree was contained to the classics: dance shoes, museums, food, and a pair of gloves. 
</p>
