<p>
	One peculiarity of living in the San Francisco Bay Area is that one acquires an excessive interest in the price of real estate in other places. Whenever I travel I seem to find myself near a real estate office listing, or a newspaper classified section, tormenting myself with the painful awareness of how much more house my dollar could buy in just about any other place on Earth than where I live. 
</p>
<p>
	American expatriates, especially people from the San Francisco and New York metro areas, have discovered Buenos Aires. Certainly there were gringos here before the devaluation, but now it's probably a lot like Prague in the 1990's: a mass of mostly young, professional-class Americans now live in this foreign city in much greater style than they can afford in the U.S. 
</p>
<p>
	I haven't read whether real estate prices are rising as a result of the expatriates, but I won't be surprised if that's happening. Meanwhile, I admit to feeling tempted by the relatively low cost of, for instance, this Art Nouveau block of flats I saw for sale in Barrio Montserrat. 
</p>
